Alright, I know the story has been jumping back and forth, but I think I have a good (possibly) final version of it that'll make it easy for us to create the game around
So, Black Reach is a company that specializes in weapons manufacturing, especially in the unnamed department. Due to an issue with the central AI that is in control of all of the "bots" developed by the company, it turns them against the very people they were designed to protect. A group of 4 employees are then tasked with traversing the facility as they make their way to the Phoenix, the AI Core in control of the "bots"

I think its better to make the setting around the year 2030 and make the bots specialized in combat (explaining the reason why they can shoot at the players). Also, the setting inside the facility makes it easier on us to with reused assets and a shorter story/gameplay

So the Black Reach campus is comprised of 4 buildings above ground and a complex tunnel network underground. The 4 buildings are the Research, Weapons Development, Bot Development, and Administration. The buildings are accessible above ground by a tram system, which go between each building in a circle. Direct paths are only available underground. Phoenix is located under the Administration building, but is accessible underground through an entrance that is heavily guarded.
The game should be a semi-open world FPS with RPG elements. Kinda similar to Prey. Keeping the gameplay we have in mind in tact










It is very interesting that you bring up that episode with the "evolution" theme, as that is similar idea as to what I was going for in the original game story. The central (hive minded) AI would start of with the set (of recalled) bots, and would devise a plan to evolve these bots into beings that would be more superior to humans (what the AI would be doing to the bots in the factory).
The AI would concurrently be producing  (through some evolution process) a "race" of "super-bots" that would incrementally challenge the humans (and the players) and test them in various ways. The end of this process would result in a race of bots that would (ideally) have all of the best characteristics of the humans that they have been challenging / learning / developing from, but would also include many other enhancements / augmentations as well.
These bots, in some sense, would be a "superior clone" to the humans that the AI has set out to replace them with.

Actually this may very much relate to what @Dibbie  wrote about the fact that a rule for  "if human, don't harm" has never been written, just  "if task not complete, find a better way to solve it. No morals" . Perhaps, the AI has seen that its own human creators may inherently lack morals necessary to keep them from killing the everything essentially, so the AI devised a plan / series of tests to continuously challenge and refine humanity as to  put them on a path "into a better tomorrow".  In this reality, there are may be many classes of bots, and the AI is slowly gaining access to all of these bots to assist it in carrying out these series of tests of the humans. The fact that a team of 4 was sent to destroy the AI core would only be proof that the AIs underline plan is working, and the game would then be the progression of this team as they move toward completing there objective of destroying the core, and then following them as the old world that they knew crumbles to dust around them as they discover the destroying the core began a series of events to wipe out the human race as it was and replace with a superior version of itself.
Well that could be the over arching story, and we would shrink the scope for the actual game.
So this could motivated a more linear game-play with the "zones", as the AI (unbeknownst to the team / player) is leading them through a series of trials.

Well in regards to the backstory, starting from what you said in the beginning, there would be many classes of bots (the main classes would be civilian and militarized) . These were created in order to aid / augment humanity in one way or another. but in order to effectively coordinate and use all of these bots, a "master AI" was developed. The master in AI was developed as to reflect the best interest of humanity and make decisions in this regard, but it eventually came to conclusion (more or less on its own, from its own observation / volition) that the best way to help humans was actually to hurt them, and from this "pain" could the AI create better humans from the (literal) ashes of the old humans.
The AI, having control over the bots, could then re purpose them all for militarization, and this could then prompt the sending of a team to infiltrate the production / re-purposing facility and stop the AI core.
Well this would be the initial plan of the humans (a natural reaction to the AIs actions).
It could be that the bulk of the game take place inside of the facility perhaps, and as the team moves through it , they slowly begin to uncover the AIs master plot, and of course the AI then responds by trying hard to eliminate them.
@Pecks I think at the last meeting you had the idea of having some  logs or something included, and well maybe there could be logs lying around the facility of the human workers / scientists there who actually figured out the AIs plan and recorded it down in pieces before the AI took them out, and the human military team would then be finding these logs scattered throughout the facility.
I think in this way, we would just have to work on the level design for a single, futuristic bot facility (to start with at least) and we should have sufficient justification for linearized game play (as the intent is show that the AI is directly controlling the experience of the characters / players in a linear way) .
Furthermore, as the team progresses and learns more about their, it would be natural that the AI would throw more difficult (and interesting) bots at them (as the AI is still militarizing the recalled bots, and with more time, can it produce better quality military bots).

This is actually a bit of an interesting direction. This reminds of the films "I am mother" and "I am legend". In "I am mother" an AI decided / succeeded in destroying the human race, not due to a malfunction, but because it made a decision that in retrospect, seemed reasonable in some way (humans were on the verge of destroying not only themselves, but the planet as well (and they destroyed most of it already)). The AI then proceeded to create a new race of humans that had greater morality, intelligence, and adaptiveness and would be more likely to create a  "better" world. What we have now for our story would seem like the beginning of this type of event, where the AI has begun to slowly eliminate the human race because it has determined that this is the best course of action in the long term for the entire planet, but humans are of course highly resistant to this and have decided to send in forces to eliminate the AI core before it gets too far (though it may be that the humans are unaware of the AI's long term plan for complete destruction, so they may not take the threat that seriously yet).
In regards to I am legend, actually in the film "I am mother", the AI succeeded in making an ideal human leader to lead the new race of humans forward, but the final test for this leader was to kill the AI interestingly enough. In the book / film "I am legend" there is this similar concept that in order for the old world to be completely ended and for the new one to begin, all "relics of the past" must be destroyed (the killing of the AI or the death of Robert Neville ("I am legend main character").
I think there may be an interesting story to tell here actually if we can smoothly blend all of the points that we have raised here.
